Gary Danko is where I FELL IN LOVE... ...WITH RISOTTO!! OMG, I dream about their lobster and rock shrimp risotto. It was freaking DELICIOUS!! Hubby and I came here on our last Michelin Restaurant Honeymoon stop. I can't remember all the items we ordered, but their risotto is the one thing I can't stop thinking about. Fine Dining usually involves pre-fixe menus, with sometimes choices of food you can choose from. I loved that GD allows you to choose 3,4,5 course menus and you can choose from any of the courses. If you wanted to, you could choose 5 appetizers or 5 desserts, or 5 entrees if you'd like! Depending on what you choose, price is based on the 3,4, or 5 courses. I loved their lobster. It was cooked really well and so juicy. I wish I had more scallops if I could, too. Everything was delicious! But the risotto was what did it for me. Oh my goodness!! Hubby had ordered a corn chowder while I ordered the risotto. He tried some of mine and then kept going back for more! I had to fight him off of my bowl of risotto!! It was so good! Really creamy, tender risotto. Service is excellent. Compared to TFL or Cyrus, I'd have to say TFL and Cyrus had better service. But GD is still up there! Ambience: Definitely romantic, dim lighting. You sit close to other couples/groups. We sat next to an older couple who were celebrating their anniversary and they come to GD every year to celebrate! Nice to talk to an older couple who've been married for much longer. For ambience, the only minor "complaint" I have is that it's a little loud, but not too bad. Parking: I suggest going Valet. Even though it's expensive, we parked at the Garage and it cost us more to pay at the garage than to valet the car. Too bad we didn't know about this until after we already parked! If I'm ever back in the Bay area, I hope to make a reservation to GD again!

This place is fancy but it's all worth it. We were seated 10minutes later than our reservation time. They gave us a couple of freebies which are good too. We'll probably be back here either Valentine's day or our anniversary again.

When I think of Gary Danko, I think of 1- the impeccable wait service and 2 - the food - it definitely lived up to the hype. You can do a la cart or choose from 3, 4, or 5 courses and the best part of that you can choose from anything off the menu and they will proportion your meal. Great cheese selections as well. The atmosphere is very relaxed and not snobbish type of fine dining feel. We even got a take home gift. Will be back again.

Had the 4 course - Tuna tartare, Filet, Dungeness crab salad and Straberry souffle. Oustanding food and service. Continues to be one of my favorite restaurants in the city with La Follie.

I guess i may not be alone on this one... feeling like the service has dwindled over the years. No, we weren't patronized, thankfully... but somewhere after the entrees were served everyone disappeared. Come cheese and dessert, I had to wave (you know, the abnoxious hand gesticulation which is reserved for flaggin' down dimsum carts?) to see about ordering a dessert wine. I really wanted to contribute to the genteel ambiance, but the lack of attention made it impossible. Salmon was not memorable, I will skip that next time. Two things to come back for: 1) Beluga caviar service, which apparently, is not contra-band Russian, but Iranian. 2) The fromage which is always a delight!

After 1099 reviews there is not much I can add to the glistening reviews of Gary Danko, other than: Service: impeccable, flawless, stupendous Cheese: F#@*ING amazing Elderflower Champagne Cocktail: simply divine Salmon Dish: my favorite off the Autumn menu...I had the Tasting Menu w/ wine pairing. Branzini: hubby had this dish and it was PERFECT!!! SO GOOD!! Portions: just right. I was full after my 2nd course. Guess my eyes were bigger than my stomach when I thought I'd be able to handle a 5 course meal. Valet: as we exited the door, our car was waiting for us at the curb. Special Occasion: plate of little treats perched atop a a plate with "Happy Anniversary" written in chocolate sauce with a candle. The reasons why I gave it 4 stars (4.5 actually), as opposed to 5: Steak: pretty good, but too much going on for my simple steak palate ( I love just the meat with some seasoning) Chocolate Souffle: I was somewhat disappointed, the center was almost too watery and I left half of the dessert, which is a shock, since I consider myself a die hard chocolate addict. ???: oddly enough, i felt like something was missing. I LOVED the experience, but for a reason I cannot pinpoint, more like a gut feeling, I wasn't blown away by the experience.

Does this restaurant need another raving review? I thought no... But after eleven sleepness nights thinking about it, I thought I'd give myself a break and write another one. Okay, yes the food is good. You can check out everyone's detailed review on each menu. I'm pretty sure with the amount of reviews here for GD, you can find one for every thing in the menu, except maybe the bacon wrapped frog legs which were were amazingly good. I think about that dish everyday... I am here to write about the service. I mean, are they kidding?!! How did they do that? This team tag waiting was crazy! I keep watching the servers to see when they communicate that we need water, or our tables need clearing, etc, but nothing. No secret eye blinks, twitchy noses, they just all automatically work together flawlessly to give you the best service. There doesn't seem to be hierarchy here, this is no Michael Jordan team. And it is well played! Upon arrival our coats were taken away and two staff were awaiting to put them back on us by the door three hours later when we were leaving. During dinner, my boyfriend really liked the wine and asked for its name again and the year, the server Darrin gave it to him. At his own initiative at the end of the meal he also gave us an envelope with a card inside with the Winery's name, the year of the wine, the website, and the phone #. The hostess left her podium to personally escort me to the restroom when I asked her where it was. Each server checked on every table quietly (not your typical obligatory "is everything okay") The servers seemed to match the customers service needs. They were respectfully polite to people on 1st dates, more relaxed with my boyfriend and I who were laughing and joking the entire night. At the end of the meal, tipping 25% seemed small for how well the service staff treated us here. I kept thinking of some of the best restaurants in SF where I thought it was not fair to tip the server based on the excellent but pricey food because the service was average or mediocre. Kudos for your great service, GD! In this economy, the only thing that would really get me to keep eating at nicer places is how well the staff treats its customers.

My advice: Stick with the four course meal. I have a huge appetite and I didn't come close to finishing all five of my wonderful courses. Overall, this was a five star experience. "I wanted a snack, so I went to Gary Danko" Ok, so in all seriousness, GD has things down. Fabulous food, AMAZING service, great ambiance, reasonably affordable, overall it was just a top-notch dining experience. Personally, it's 2nd to Jean Georges in NYC but I haven't tried French Laundry or Guy Savoy (among other places). One thing though, for a classy place like this, the portions were shockingly large! Here I was thinking I was going to get some crazy vertical pieces of food with a total volume of 1 cubic inch, but WOW, they really feed you. I'd like to thank Yelp for leading me to this place. I recently looked at all of my reviews and thought hey, I seem to have a lot of 4-5 star reviews. Is it because I'm an easy reviewer? Perhaps, but I also think I go to a lot of 4-5 star places thanks to Yelp. And Yelp, you've done it again. Actually, if there was a way to give it 6 stars, I'd do it - just like Skytrax. Perhaps the best meal I've ever had in my life. We went with the five course tasting menu, and there was not a single misstep in any course or in the service, as you'd expect for a restaurant of this caliber. I'll say you really can't go wrong with anything on the menu - but I can still imagine that risotto, soft shell crab, and that stuffed quail. Five really filling and amazing dishes made for a really memorable evening of food and fun. I cannot wait to come back again. Run, don't walk, Gary Danko.

There is SOOOO much to say and so little space...actually no...I'm going to say it all. Gary Danko's was more than I expected it to be. It was the bf's birthday. Now mind you, the bf is a picky eater and hasn't had a lot of experience with 5 star restaraunts, but still...perfect. We got there ahead of our reservation time, hoping to get an earlier seating than 9:00 p.m., for a Tuesday, I was surprised how many people were in there. Its not a quiet atmosphere to say the least and its a lot smaller inside than I thought it would be. We took a seat at the bar while we waited for our table. It was a while, but we were sipping on a couple of cocktails so we were perfectly allright. We were gently tapped on the shoulder to be taken to our table at around 9. Everyone talks about the service here, these people are super nice and actually seem like they want to work there. We sit and our awesome waiter explains to us the menu and our options for dining. We decide to go with the three courses. I was a little worried because I thought maybe it wouldn't be enough and I wanted to experience Danko's to its fullness...wrong! Round 1 We were treated to a taste of the butternut squash soup, which we both agreed was PERFECTly seasoned and a great way to get our tastebuds ready for what was to come. Round 2 For appetizers the bf decided I should order so I did. He had the lobster and I had the scallops. The great thing about Danko's is that you can choose food from any course and they will turn it into any course. The scallops....WOW...perfectly braised, I don't even like raisens and I ate those. As for the lobster, I think my bf was having a bit too good a time with those, because I didn't get to taste any of it, sniff! At this point I'm a little worried because the portions seemed a little small...but wait...its just the appetizer course. Our waiter graciously paired our appetizer with a sparkling wine that fit quite nicely with our seafood. Round 3 The main course, Beef Tenderloin....mmmmmm....At this point my belly is starting to get full. We took one bite into this succulent piece of meat and new that this is how filet was supposed to taste. The potatoes were excellent, but the meat...oh the meat. I almost couldn't finish I started feeling so surprisingly full. Round 4 The infamous cheese plate. After garcon explained the various tastes/textures of the cheeses to us we chose five to taste. The grapes were delightfully helpful in cleansing the pallet and the bread pieces were perfect to try the cheese. Our waiter also paired this course with Lucky 7....and boy was it lucky. I'm full and tipsy by this time. We weren't able to finish the cheeses and I think my boyfriend was out of his body by this point. Round 5 The bf has given up, I have one more round to go....Chocolate Souflee. I had NO clue that I would be sooo full by this time. The birthday boy had a cup of coffee while I played with the souflee, delish! It was chocolatey but not overwhelming with chocolate. We were both in a food coma by this time and ready to go to sleep all cozy in our beds. The waiter brought out a little happy birthday cookie plate for my man, who was quite surprised and super thankful to be brought to Danko's. I was worried that his pickiness may have been a problem, since there was so many unknown French named dishes on the menu, but since he let me choose everything it worked out beautifully. The food was A+, the service was A+, the night was A+. As we left Danko's, my boyfriend had only one thing to say sarcastically, "Gary's not back there!" :)... It was a perfect birthday experience.

A year ago (January 15, 2008) I wrote a polite letter to the restaurant: "Our dinner with you about five years ago was stunningly wonderful. We've held it up as dining perfection to ourselves and to friends... There was a lot less magic and a lot more ordinariness in our 2008 evening with you." Then I wrote five short paragraphs about stuff which disturbed us at the dinner we had had on the 13th. They were mostly about the atmosphere with loud cell phone conversations, intrusive flash cameras, and generally harried staff not taking care of the restaurant. I ended with: "I am writing to you because we love splurging on wonderful meals. Our earlier experience at Gary Danko was one of the most wonderful we have ever had. We want you to live up to that memory again in the future. "I don't want apologies, discounts, or anything from this letter. However, I would like to read somewhere that you've recovered from a bad spell. Or, let us hear that Gary has spent time on the floor and fixed things. Send us a note in a few months - a year, whenever it's true - to let us know it would be safe to trust you again." I have heard nothing from them in the past year. I think it's fair at this time to judge Gary Danko as being unreliable in its service and attention to its clients. It can be a perfect evening. It can be a distracted mess.

My friends and I came here as a final splurge to officially end our vacation. Once you come back from Japan, everything else - including Gary Danko - looks somewhat reasonably priced in comparison. Ambiance and Decor: GD looks bigger from the outside. I walked in expecting a big dining area like Harris' but instead only saw a small dining area to my right (I didn't venture to the area on my left because I had no reason to enter that area). Our table for three felt cramped, probably because it was meant for couples who want to be close together. The decoration is old school, classic with some contemporary twists. Food: We each got three courses and added in a cheese course. As is our custom, we use our appetizer plates to sample each others' food ala Costco. I devoured the oyster appetizer (after having to part with two of them to my friends) and have no guilt admitting that. My friend had the risotto, which was also good but not as memorable as the oysters. I chose the lobster while my friends got the bison and seared beef for entrees. The joy I had in the oysters was diminished because I really REALLY loved the beef entree, only that wasn't my entree so I could only sample it. *tear* It wasn't that the lobster and bison weren't good but the beef surpassed both those dishes so that both, more so the lobster than the bison, tasted bland in comparison. After seeing so many pictures and raves about the chocolate souffle, of course we ordered that in addition to the trio of creme brulee and rhubarb tart. They were good but I wouldn't come here just for the dessert as I would with Roy's chocolate souffle. The creme brulee and tart are what you'd expect from this type of restaurant. The souffle is much lighter than what you'd normally get, which is probably why I am not thrilled with it. The texture is almost to that of a dense soup. To top off the night, you get a muffin for the next day, if you can still eat after digesting for 8 hours. Service: No complaints whatsoever about the wait staff. They were courteous to us from the moment we stepped into the place until we left. They're attentive (except for one time when we couldn't find out waiter) without being too much in your face. All was forgiven when a waiter - not the one assigned to us - gave us a plate of bite-sized cookies on the house. The total per person with one drink was $100.

There are not enough stars to give to this restaurant. I've been fortunate to dine there on three occasions and each of them have been amazing experiences. Starting with the service...impeccable. My head was spinning at the attention I was given. And the fact that you never seemed to have the same waiter was amazing. Each one of them had an incredible amount of knowledge regarding the courses. Courses...I've had many and the one that always comes to mind is the cheese course. Do not pass up this opportunity. I could go on and on about Gary Danko but from looking at the other reviews there is nothing I would say that hasn't already been said. I can't wait for the new location to open just down the street at Ghiradelli Square.

You know, I hate to be a downer as so many people have given such stellar reviews - maybe that's why my expectations were so high. Don't get me wrong, the ambience, service and presentation were all excellent and I have no complaints about that, but the food wasn't as outstanding as some of the places I've been to with the same kind of price-tag (e.g. Le Jardiniere). I started with the oysters, followed by the frogs' legs, followed by the guinea fowl, and all were just too salty. Now, I like salty over sweet any day of the week, and I usually add salt (or soy sauce) to any dish I eat because I like it that way, but it just seemed heavy-handed in the salt department from the get-go. Mind you, the only thing I couldn't eat was the "sausage" that went with the guinea fowl - that was a solid bit of seriously over-salty something un-sausage-like to me, so it's not like I would have complained about any of the dishes were it not for the exorbitant price tag. (Dessert wasn't salty, though - I had the chestnut mousse dome which was quite good.) Don't get me wrong - it was all very good, but I wouldn't put it in the "outstanding" category. I'm trying to be open-minded - maybe I just mis-chose my dishes? Maybe I'm just spoiled?

Lady friend and I arrived 5pm Saturday to get bar seating, which had really attentive service anyway. If you're first in line, you might get lucky and snag the one (or more) table not reserved until 7pm. We were stuffed after sharing the Foie Gras Tasting Menu and four other courses. Note: portions are sized depending on how much food you order. (The scallop dish might come with 1-2 scallops in your four-course meal but with four scallops if you only ordered an appetizer and an entree.) Foie Gras Tasting Menu $150: we absolutely loved almost every bite. + Foie Gras Torchon with Grape Terrine and Brioche: a good portion of slightly-above-standard foie gras torchon on my favorite brioche, enhanced by the refreshing grape and a delicious candied jam. + Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Cherries: I hate cooked/prepared/sauced cherries, so I had the seared foie with just a little bit of the onions; by the end I just had the foie gras alone since I didn't want it to be tainted with other flavors. + Foie Gras Custard with Shitake Mushrooms, Scallions, and Dashi: weakest dish on the menu, but still enjoyable. Pretty standard-quality Asian steamed egg custard, foie gras was a nice addition. + Squab Breast with Grits, Fava Beans, Leeks and Foie Gras Pistachio Croutons: really unique foie gras preparation as the side of ~5 bite-sized slices of wonderfully-still-slightly-red squab breast. + Foie Gras Profiteroles with Huckleberries: I loved smearing the huckleberry sauce onto the profiteroles but did not like eating the actual huckleberries with the profiteroles; really subtle foie gras flavor as the last bite of the meal. Self-selected four-course menu $89: hit & miss - amazing hits but one or two misses. + Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Mushrooms, Asparagus and Peas - huge chunks of seafood; I could eat just this dish every day for the rest of my life and be satisfied. + Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon: also fantastic - sauced with a really great buttery fish broth. - Soft shell crab with bacon grits: we both hated it; way too much bacon, red pepper, etc. If you like soft shell crab prepared by Japanese restaurants, DO NOT GET THIS. - Juniper Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spaetzle: in my mind I mixed up bison and caribou and was expecting really tender meat. This is not it. Sigh. Spaetzle's not bad, but I wouldn't get this again. I regret having only had once (years ago) the quail stuffed with quinoa, foie gras, mushroom, etc., but I'm also excited to see what they come up with to replace this dish (or just the foie gras flavor - it's not like they stuff chunks of it in the quail anyway) come July 1. Note: If you love a good ol' Old Fashioned, do NOT get the one they make here. Small ice pieces melt and dilute the drink too quickly. Orange flavor too strong.

    7/13/2009

    My friends and I came here as a final splurge to officially end our vacation. Once you come back from Japan, everything else - including Gary Danko - looks somewhat reasonably priced in comparison.

    Ambiance and Decor: GD looks bigger from the outside. I walked in expecting a big dining area like Harris' but instead only saw a small dining area to my right (I didn't venture to the area on my left because I had no reason to enter that area). Our table for three felt cramped, probably because it was meant for couples who want to be close together. The decoration is old school, classic with some contemporary twists.

    Food: We each got three courses and added in a cheese course. As is our custom, we use our appetizer plates to sample each others' food ala Costco. I devoured the oyster appetizer (after having to part with two of them to my friends) and have no guilt admitting that. My friend had the risotto, which was also good but not as memorable as the oysters.

    I chose the lobster while my friends got the bison and seared beef for entrees. The joy I had in the oysters was diminished because I really REALLY loved the beef entree, only that wasn't my entree so I could only sample it. *tear* It wasn't that the lobster and bison weren't good but the beef surpassed both those dishes so that both, more so the lobster than the bison, tasted bland in comparison.

    After seeing so many pictures and raves about the chocolate souffle, of course we ordered that in addition to the trio of creme brulee and rhubarb tart. They were good but I wouldn't come here just for the dessert as I would with Roy's chocolate souffle. The creme brulee and tart are what you'd expect from this type of restaurant. The souffle is much lighter than what you'd normally get, which is probably why I am not thrilled with it. The texture is almost to that of a dense soup. To top off the night, you get a muffin for the next day, if you can still eat after digesting for 8 hours.

    Service: No complaints whatsoever about the wait staff. They were courteous to us from the moment we stepped into the place until we left. They're attentive (except for one time when we couldn't find out waiter) without being too much in your face. All was forgiven when a waiter - not the one assigned to us - gave us a plate of bite-sized cookies on the house.

    The total per person with one drink was $100.

    6/24/2012

    Lady friend and I arrived 5pm Saturday to get bar seating, which had really attentive service anyway. If you're first in line, you might get lucky and snag the one (or more) table not reserved until 7pm.

    We were stuffed after sharing the Foie Gras Tasting Menu and four other courses. Note: portions are sized depending on how much food you order. (The scallop dish might come with 1-2 scallops in your four-course meal but with four scallops if you only ordered an appetizer and an entree.)

    Foie Gras Tasting Menu $150: we absolutely loved almost every bite.
    + Foie Gras Torchon with Grape Terrine and Brioche: a good portion of slightly-above-standard foie gras torchon on my favorite brioche, enhanced by the refreshing grape and a delicious candied jam.
    + Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Cherries: I hate cooked/prepared/sauced cherries, so I had the seared foie with just a little bit of the onions; by the end I just had the foie gras alone since I didn't want it to be tainted with other flavors.
    + Foie Gras Custard with Shitake Mushrooms, Scallions, and Dashi: weakest dish on the menu, but still enjoyable. Pretty standard-quality Asian steamed egg custard, foie gras was a nice addition.
    + Squab Breast with Grits, Fava Beans, Leeks and Foie Gras Pistachio Croutons: really unique foie gras preparation as the side of ~5 bite-sized slices of wonderfully-still-slightly-red squab breast.
    + Foie Gras Profiteroles with Huckleberries: I loved smearing the huckleberry sauce onto the profiteroles but did not like eating the actual huckleberries with the profiteroles; really subtle foie gras flavor as the last bite of the meal.

    Self-selected four-course menu $89: hit & miss - amazing hits but one or two misses.
    + Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Mushrooms, Asparagus and Peas - huge chunks of seafood; I could eat just this dish every day for the rest of my life and be satisfied.
    + Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon: also fantastic - sauced with a really great buttery fish broth.
    - Soft shell crab with bacon grits: we both hated it; way too much bacon, red pepper, etc. If you like soft shell crab prepared by Japanese restaurants, DO NOT GET THIS.
    - Juniper Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spaetzle: in my mind I mixed up bison and caribou and was expecting really tender meat. This is not it. Sigh. Spaetzle's not bad, but I wouldn't get this again.

    I regret having only had once (years ago) the quail stuffed with quinoa, foie gras, mushroom, etc., but I'm also excited to see what they come up with to replace this dish (or just the foie gras flavor - it's not like they stuff chunks of it in the quail anyway) come July 1.

    Note: If you love a good ol' Old Fashioned, do NOT get the one they make here. Small ice pieces melt and dilute the drink too quickly. Orange flavor too strong.
